\subsection{Broad context and the problem}
\label{sec:broad_context}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Artificial light provides an indispensable energy service (illumination), 
enabling activities at times when natural light levels are insufficient.
Artificial illumination is so valuable that around 20~\% of global grid-connected electricity 
is consumed for the purpose of making light~\cite{waide2006}.
With the modern breakthrough technology of light emitting diode (LED) lamps,
which now comprise 40~\% of residential lamp sales~\cite{IEA2019},
applications have spread beyond illumination to many other fields
including human physiology and photosynthesis for horticulture~\cite{Pattison2018LEDefficacy}.
The use and analysis of the energy and exergy efficiency of lighting is applied to a range of fields,
including energy economics (***REF***),
societal exergy analysis~\cite{Ayres2005},
energy history~\cite{Fouquet:2006},
and forecasting energy efficiency improvements~\cite{IEA2019}.
However, a key problem arises for the energy analyst:
there are differing concepts and definitions of lighting efficiency.
These differences matter on two counts.
First, with the rise of LED lamps,
the proximity to the efficiency limits of lighting appears within reach – but what is the limit?
Second, given the expanding role that artificial lighting plays globally,
understanding precisely 
its potential contribution---via increasing efficiency---to reducing energy use
to meet carbon dioxide emission targets is crucially important.
The aim of this paper is therefore to bring clarity to the analyst 
on the definitions of the energy and exergy conversion efficiency of artificial light for illumination.
We exclude non-illumination purposes, such as horticulture and heating, 
**** and our focus is societal exergy analysis. ****


