The second fundamental aspect of light is that 
modern lighting is provided by energy conversion through three stages
of the energy conversion chain:
primary energy (e.g., coal), which is then converted to
final energy (i.e., electricity, measured in watts), and last to
useful energy output (i.e., the provision of visible light energy, measured in lumens).
The efficiency of energy conversion~($\eta$) from the final stage (electricity) 
to the useful stage (light) is the focus of this paper.
We note that both human perception and satisfaction of human needs
are an energy service (illumination),
which occurs after the useful stage.


