%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy-to-energy ratio of EM radiation, $\phi_{\EM}$ (Zeke and Emmanuel, 500 words)}
\label{sec:phi_light}
%------------------------------

Recent advances in the thermodynamics of radiation community
enable converting the energy of EM radiation into the exergy of EM radiation.
The exergy-to-energy ratio of EM radiation
($\phi_{\EM}$, called the ``radiative exergy-energy coefficient'' in that community)
is given by Petela's Equation~\cite{petela1964exergy}:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:petelas_equation}
 \phi_{\EM} = 1 - \frac{4}{3}\frac{T_{0}}{T_{1}} + \frac{1}{3} \left(\frac{T_{0}}{T_{1}}\right)^4 \; .
\end{equation}

However, Petela's equation assumes a blackbody emitter and
a blackbody absorber 
at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_0$, respectively.
To determine $\phi_{\EM}$ for a non-blackbody lamp,
the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio ($\phi_{\EM,\lambda}$),
must be calculated.
An effective temperature of light photons~\cite{chen2008} ($T_\lambda$) 
provides the link between Petela's equation (Equation~\ref{eq:petelas_equation})
and the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_{\EM,\lambda}$).
(We note that the use of the photon effective temperature approach has been criticized by 
\citet[p.~1810]{liu2009},
who argued that 
``to endue a single photon with macro-scale thermodynamic parameters
such as exergy and entropy'' is inappropriate.
We acknowledge this critique, 
but we also note that here $T_\lambda$ is ascribed to a stream of photons
traveling from a lamp to an eye.
Thus, for our purposes, $T_\lambda$ can be considered the statistical average effective temperature 
of the stream of photons.
