Previously, societal exergy analysis adopted the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
when calculating the exergetic efficiency of lighting.
(See Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach}.)

The choice of any weighting function is a subjective decision for the analyst,
however to provide consistency for SEA community moving forward
we propose to adopt the universal luminosity function in accordance with \citet{Rea2018},
\emph{if} the assumption is made that lamps are solely used for illumination in society.
A more comprehensive approach would be to select a representative range of uses for lamps,
which are then assessed based on their respective weighting functions.

Given that the industry-standard measure of lighting efficiency
is the luminous efficacy~($K$),
the use of the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
under-represents the power at short wavelengths in lighting efficiency estimates.
This state of affairs biases lighting manufacturers to reduce short wavelength
output of lamps, even when short wavelength EM radiation would be beneficial
for biological regulation. 


